<TITLE> Docu fest starts Thursday </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Apr 15 (bdnews24.com)  A four-day documentary festival starts Thursday at the Central Public Library in the capital. Forty selected documentaries, made from 2007-09, will be displayed in the festival styled 'Bangladesh Documentary Festival 2009', said Fouzia Khan, president, Bangladesh Pramanyachitra Porshod, organiser of the festival, at a press conference at the National Museum. The reels will tell the stories of marginalised people, psychology of urban teens, Jatrapala, life of a cleaner or a goldsmith as well as the stories of the independence war, the victory and the 1952 Language Movement. The show will be open tom all for free on the first day. 'National professor' Kabir Chowdhury will inaugurate the festival. Novelist and critique Syed Shamsul Haque will distribute prizes among the winners at the closing ceremony. Manjare Hasin Murad, film director and an adviser to the Porshod; Mainul Huda of Steps Towards Development and Farhana Hafiz Tania of Oxfam GB, were present at the press conference. Seminars, roundtables and views-exchange meetings will also be arranged. bdnews24.com, ATN Bangla and ABC Radio are the media partners of the festival. Documentary festivals were arranged in Dhaka in 2005 and 2007. bdne
